## Memory Leak Analysis: `ScrollTracker`

There are **three distinct bugs** working together to cause this leak. Here's a full breakdown.

---

## Bug #1 — Missing Dependency Array (Effect Runs on Every Render)

```jsx
// ❌ No dependency array — runs after EVERY render
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
});
```

Without a dependency array, React re-runs this effect after **every single render**. The scroll handler itself calls three state setters (`setScrollDirection`, `setLastScrollY`, `setScrollY`). Each setter triggers a re-render. Each re-render triggers the effect again. Each effect run adds **two brand new event listeners** to `window` without ever removing the previous ones.

**The cascade:**
```
user scrolls → handler fires → 3x setState → re-render → effect runs again
→ 2 NEW listeners added → user scrolls → 6 handlers fire → 6x setState → ...
```

After just a few scroll events, `window` has dozens of active listeners from a single component instance.

---

## Bug #2 — No Cleanup Function (Listeners Survive Unmount)

```jsx
useEffect(() => {
    window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { ... });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => { ... });
    // ❌ No return () => { removeEventListener(...) }
});
```

`useEffect` can return a cleanup function that React calls when the component **unmounts** (navigating away) or before the effect **re-runs**. Without it:

- When the user navigates away, the component is destroyed, but **both listeners remain attached to `window`**
- Each listener's closure holds references to the component's state setter functions, keeping that memory alive and **preventing garbage collection**
- Navigating back mounts a **fresh component instance** with its own new listeners — the old ones are still running in the background

After navigating away and back N times, there are N sets of orphaned listeners all fighting to update state on a component that no longer exists.

---

## Bug #3 — Anonymous Arrow Functions Can't Be Removed

```jsx
// The function passed here...
window.addEventListener('scroll', () => { setScrollY(window.scrollY); });

// ...cannot be matched by removeEventListener, because arrow functions
// create a new object identity every time they're evaluated:
window.removeEventListener('scroll', () => { setScrollY(window.scrollY); }); // ❌ different reference, no-op
```

`removeEventListener` uses **reference equality** to find and remove the target handler. An anonymous arrow function creates a new function object every time the expression is evaluated — the function you pass to `removeEventListener` is a completely different object from the one you passed to `addEventListener`, so the removal silently fails. You **must** hold a stable reference to the exact same function to remove it.

---

## React 18 Strict Mode Makes This Immediately Visible

In development, React 18's `<StrictMode>` intentionally **double-invokes effects**:

```
Mount → run effect → [Strict Mode: run cleanup] → re-run effect
```

If there's no cleanup function, the "run cleanup" step is a no-op, and the re-run step adds a second set of listeners before the user has even interacted with the page. What would normally take several scroll events to manifest now shows up immediately on first mount — Strict Mode acts as a built-in amplifier for this exact class of bug.

> Note: Strict Mode double-invocation only happens in **development** builds. Production does not double-invoke, but the leak still exists — it just accumulates more slowly.

---

## The Complete Corrected Component

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect, useRef } from 'react';

function ScrollTracker() {
    const [scrollY, setScrollY] = useState(0);
    const [scrollDirection, setScrollDirection] = useState('none');

    // useRef instead of useState for lastScrollY:
    //   - It doesn't need to trigger a re-render (it's intermediate tracking state)
    //   - Avoids a stale closure: the ref object is stable, so handleScroll always
    //     reads the current value without needing to be recreated or listed as a dep
    const lastScrollYRef = useRef(0);

    useEffect(() => {
        // ✅ Named functions — stable references that removeEventListener can match
        function handleScroll() {
            const currentScrollY = window.scrollY;

            // Read and write the ref directly — no re-render, no stale closure
            setScrollDirection(currentScrollY > lastScrollYRef.current ? 'down' : 'up');
            lastScrollYRef.current = currentScrollY;
            setScrollY(currentScrollY);
        }

        function handleResize() {
            console.log('Window resized, recalculating...');
            setScrollY(window.scrollY);
        }

        // ✅ Register listeners once on mount
        window.addEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
        window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);

        // ✅ Cleanup: runs on unmount AND before the effect would re-run
        //    Removes the exact same function references registered above
        return () => {
            window.removeEventListener('scroll', handleScroll);
            window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
        };

    }, []); // ✅ Empty array: effect runs exactly once (on mount), cleans up on unmount

    return (
        <div style={{ position: 'fixed', top: 10, right: 10, padding: '10px', background: '#333', color: '#fff' }}>
            <p>Scroll Y: {scrollY}</p>
            <p>Direction: {scrollDirection}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

export default ScrollTracker;
```

---

## Summary of All Changes

| Problem | Root Cause | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Listeners multiply on every render | No dependency array → effect re-runs on every state change | Add `[]` — effect runs once on mount |
| Listeners survive unmount | No cleanup function | Return `() => removeEventListener(...)` from effect |
| Cleanup can't find the right listener | Anonymous functions have new identity each call | Extract named `handleScroll` / `handleResize` functions |
| Stale `lastScrollY` closure | `useState` value captured at effect-creation time | Replace with `useRef` — always reads the live current value |

The corrected component registers exactly two listeners on mount and removes exactly those two on unmount, regardless of how many times the user navigates away and back.

